From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000007 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: NixOS module overlay <noreply@example.com>
Date: Wed, 8 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 7/7] Raise the per-user upload queue limit for self-hosted

Upstream zotero/dataserver caps each user to 10 in-flight upload URL
requests in any 5-minute window:

    public static $uploadQueueLimit = 10;
    public static $uploadQueueTimeout = 300;

When the limit is exceeded the dataserver responds with HTTP 413 and
the desktop client surfaces it as a generic "file sync error" — exactly
the same UI as the storage-quota and attachment-body-size walls, with
no useful diagnostics distinguishing it from any other failure.

This is fine on hosted zotero.org where it's a per-account anti-abuse
limit on a multi-tenant system, but it's the wrong default for a
self-hosted single-user (or small-team) deployment, where the only
client is *your* client and a single Restore-to-Online migration of an
established library will routinely queue dozens of uploads in a single
batch. Each previous failure (e.g. quota wall, body-size wall) leaves
its row in storageUploadQueue for 5 full minutes, so even after fixing
the underlying problem the queue stays "full" and every retry gets
413'd until the row ages out.

Bump the limit to 200. Still bounded — a runaway client can't DoS the
server — but high enough that no realistic single-user workload will
ever notice. The 300-second timeout is left untouched so genuinely
stale entries still age out.
---
diff --git a/model/Storage.inc.php b/model/Storage.inc.php
index 1234567..89abcde 100644
--- a/model/Storage.inc.php
+++ b/model/Storage.inc.php
@@ -26,7 +26,9 @@
 	// Self-hosted: default to effectively unlimited (10 TB in MB).
 	// Per-user overrides via storageAccounts still work as before.
 	public static $defaultQuota = 10485760;
-	public static $uploadQueueLimit = 10;
+	// Self-hosted: raise the per-user in-flight upload queue limit
+	// from the zotero.org abuse-prevention default of 10 to 200.
+	public static $uploadQueueLimit = 200;
 	public static $uploadQueueTimeout = 300;
 	private static $s3PresignedRequestTTL = 3600;

